# File: tests/features/large-response-detection.feature
#
# Generated from: specs/feature-add-large-response-detection-with-guided-search-and-full-response-override/requirements.md
# Issues: #168, #177

Feature: Large Response Detection with Temp File Output
  As an AI agent consuming agentchrome output
  I want large command outputs automatically written to the OS temp directory with the file path returned on stdout
  So that I can access complete data without consuming excessive context budget or requiring re-invocation

  Background:
    Given a connected Chrome session

  # --- Core Temp File Output (AC18) ---

  Scenario: Large response writes to temp file and returns output object
    Given a page with an accessibility tree exceeding 16 KB when serialized
    When I run "page snapshot"
    Then stdout contains valid JSON with "output_file" as a string
    And stdout contains "size_bytes" as a positive integer
    And stdout contains "command" set to "page snapshot"
    And stdout contains a "summary" object
    And the exit code is 0

  Scenario: Temp file path points to a readable file in the OS temp directory
    Given a page with an accessibility tree exceeding 16 KB when serialized
    When I run "page snapshot"
    Then the "output_file" value is a path to an existing file
    And the file path starts with the OS temp directory
    And the file name matches the pattern "agentchrome-*.json"

  # --- Temp File Content Integrity (AC19) ---

  Scenario: Temp file contains complete unmodified JSON output
    Given a page with an accessibility tree exceeding 16 KB when serialized
    When I run "page snapshot"
    Then reading the file at "output_file" returns valid JSON
    And the file JSON contains the accessibility tree with node data
    And the file JSON matches the normal page snapshot output schema

  # --- Below-Threshold Responses (AC5) ---

  Scenario: Below-threshold responses are returned inline
    Given a page with an accessibility tree under 16 KB when serialized
    When I run "page snapshot"
    Then stdout contains the full accessibility tree JSON
    And stdout does not contain "output_file"
    And the exit code is 0

  # --- UUID Collision Prevention (AC20) ---

  Scenario: Concurrent commands produce distinct temp files
    Given a page with content exceeding 16 KB
    When I run "page snapshot" and "page text" concurrently
    Then each command returns a different "output_file" path
    And both files exist and are readable

  # --- Output Object Schema Consistency (AC21) ---

  Scenario: Output object has exactly four fields across all commands
    Given a page with content exceeding 16 KB
    When I run "page snapshot"
    Then the output JSON has exactly these top-level keys: "output_file", "size_bytes", "command", "summary"
    When I run "page text"
    Then the output JSON has exactly these top-level keys: "output_file", "size_bytes", "command", "summary"

  # --- Threshold Configuration (AC6, AC7) ---

  Scenario: Threshold is configurable via CLI flag - above threshold
    Given a page producing 20 KB of serialized JSON output
    When I run "page snapshot --large-response-threshold 8192"
    Then stdout contains "output_file"

  Scenario: Threshold is configurable via CLI flag - below threshold
    Given a page producing 20 KB of serialized JSON output
    When I run "page snapshot --large-response-threshold 32768"
    Then stdout contains the full accessibility tree JSON
    And stdout does not contain "output_file"

  Scenario: Threshold is configurable via config file
    Given a config file with "large_response_threshold = 8192" under "[output]"
    And a page producing 10 KB of serialized JSON output
    When I run "page snapshot"
    Then stdout contains "output_file"

  Scenario: CLI threshold flag overrides config file
    Given a config file with "large_response_threshold = 8192" under "[output]"
    And a page producing 10 KB of serialized JSON output
    When I run "page snapshot --large-response-threshold 32768"
    Then stdout contains the full response inline
    And stdout does not contain "output_file"

  # --- Plain Mode Temp File (AC22) ---

  Scenario: Plain mode writes to temp file when above threshold
    Given a page with an accessibility tree exceeding 16 KB when serialized
    When I run "page snapshot --plain --large-response-threshold 100"
    Then stdout contains a file path ending in ".txt"
    And the file at that path contains plain-text accessibility tree output

  Scenario: Plain mode returns inline when below threshold
    Given a page with an accessibility tree under 16 KB when serialized
    When I run "page snapshot --plain"
    Then stdout contains the full plain-text accessibility tree
    And stdout does not contain ".txt"

  # --- Command-Specific Summary (AC23) ---

  Scenario: Snapshot summary contains node count and top roles
    Given a page with an accessibility tree exceeding 16 KB
    When I run "page snapshot"
    Then the "summary" object contains "total_nodes" as a positive integer
    And the "summary" object contains "top_roles" as an array of strings

  Scenario: Page text summary contains character and line counts
    Given a page with text content exceeding 16 KB
    When I run "page text"
    Then the "summary" object contains "character_count" as a positive integer
    And the "summary" object contains "line_count" as a positive integer

  # --- Existing Truncation (AC15) ---

  Scenario: Existing per-command truncation remains as second layer
    Given a page with 15000 accessibility tree nodes
    When I run "page snapshot"
    Then reading the temp file shows the tree with "truncated" set to true
    And the tree contains at most 10000 nodes

  # --- Flag Removal (AC24) ---

  Scenario: --search flag produces validation error
    When I run "page snapshot --search login"
    Then stderr contains a clap validation error for unknown argument
    And the exit code is non-zero

  Scenario: --full-response flag produces validation error
    When I run "page snapshot --full-response"
    Then stderr contains a clap validation error for unknown argument
    And the exit code is non-zero

  # Added by issue #177
